cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.NE, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with computational geometry problems related to moving points in a circular region to form a regular polygon, which is a classic problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also presents algorithms with time complexity analysis, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The problem of mobile sensor barrier coverage of wireless sensor networks mentioned in the abstract suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.NE (Networks and Internet Architecture). Finally, the paper presents an algorithm for dynamically maintaining the maximum matching of a circular convex bipartite graph, which suggests that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
